 world around him. Even before the events of 1938-39, culminating in Kristallnacht, the family was convinced that they must leave the country. Gay describes the bravery and ingenuity of his father in working out this difficult emigration process, the courage of the non-Jewish friends who helped his family during their last bitter months in Germany, and the family’s mounting panic as they witnessed the indifference of other countries to their plight and that of others like themselves. Gay’s account-marked by candor, modesty, and insight-adds an important and curiously neglected perspective to the history of German Jewry.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aJewsxPersecutionszGermanyzBerlin. 0aJewszGermanyxHistoryy1933-1945. 0aJewszGermanyzBerlin. 0aNational socialismzGermanyzBerlin. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Personal Memoirs.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030007670740uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300133141?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300133141423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300133141/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY